1
00:01:23,917 --> 00:01:25,877
[Donovan] <i>There is no corpse.</i>

2
00:01:31,758 --> 00:01:33,593
There's no corpse.

3
00:01:34,135 --> 00:01:35,470
I heard you.

4
00:01:40,809 --> 00:01:44,604
Remind Felix Manning
that I do not tolerate loose ends.

5
00:01:44,687 --> 00:01:45,897
Yes, Mr. Fisk.

6
00:01:47,023 --> 00:01:49,859
But the body was probably just swept
away in the current.

7
00:01:51,319 --> 00:01:53,404
Even if Murdock
somehow escaped from the cab,

8
00:01:53,488 --> 00:01:56,157
how does a blind man swim to shore?

9
00:01:58,576 --> 00:02:01,121
This look like a blind man to you?

10
00:02:11,881 --> 00:02:13,716
We investigated him thoroughly.

11
00:02:13,800 --> 00:02:15,051
His associates.

12
00:02:16,052 --> 00:02:18,888
Medical and school records all check out.

13
00:02:18,972 --> 00:02:22,308
All confirm that Matt Murdock
lost his sight at age nine.

14
00:02:23,268 --> 00:02:24,269
[Fisk softly] Yes.

15
00:02:25,562 --> 00:02:26,855
Nevertheless...

16
00:02:28,773 --> 00:02:31,276
a man capable of that could have survived.

17
00:02:39,826 --> 00:02:42,829
And he threatened
to come between Vanessa and I.

18
00:02:57,510 --> 00:03:00,346
[Donovan] <i>It's time for the government</i>
<i>to honor our deal.</i>

19
00:03:01,181 --> 00:03:02,557
Thanks to my client,

20
00:03:02,640 --> 00:03:05,768
the Albanian Syndicate
has been completely wiped out.

21
00:03:06,311 --> 00:03:10,815
Their counterfeiting ring,
their Dark Web child pornography.

22
00:03:11,482 --> 00:03:14,944
And the Jalisco connection
Mr. Fisk divulged last week

23
00:03:15,028 --> 00:03:19,073
gave the DEA an early
and very white Christmas.

24
00:03:19,157 --> 00:03:22,118
And in exchange
for his ongoing cooperation,

25
00:03:22,202 --> 00:03:25,788
the DOJ will not be filing charges
against Vanessa Marianna.

26
00:03:26,331 --> 00:03:30,335
Mr. Fisk is also entitled to the return
of certain personal belongings,

27
00:03:30,418 --> 00:03:32,170
supervised movement within the hotel.

28
00:03:32,253 --> 00:03:35,298
He'll get everything he was offered.
In time.

29
00:03:35,381 --> 00:03:37,842
[Donovan] That time is now,
Special Agent Nadeem.

30
00:03:39,177 --> 00:03:41,554
Unless you'd like my client
to stop talking.

31
00:03:42,764 --> 00:03:46,976
FBI has sacrificed a great deal for me.

32
00:03:50,939 --> 00:03:56,402
And I will continue to cooperate
and trust you'll honor your word.

33
00:04:03,326 --> 00:04:05,912
There's a criminal I've employed.

34
00:04:08,248 --> 00:04:09,749
A facilitator.

35
00:04:10,792 --> 00:04:13,920
On my behalf,
he's laundered and hid money,

36
00:04:14,003 --> 00:04:17,674
bribed law enforcement
and court officials,

37
00:04:17,757 --> 00:04:22,929
orchestrated perjured testimony,
manufactured evidence.

38
00:04:24,472 --> 00:04:25,556
[Ray] Who is he?

39
00:04:28,768 --> 00:04:31,813
A lawyer. Matthew Murdock.

40
00:04:36,567 --> 00:04:37,986
[theme music playing]

41
00:06:39,107 --> 00:06:40,483
Alpha Team on approach.

42
00:06:42,235 --> 00:06:43,152
[door opens]

43
00:06:43,236 --> 00:06:45,947
FBI. Get back in your apartment
and close the door.

44
00:06:51,577 --> 00:06:52,578
Stack up.

45
00:06:53,287 --> 00:06:54,247
Breach.

46
00:06:57,750 --> 00:06:58,835
[agent shouting] FBI!

47
00:07:01,045 --> 00:07:02,171
[Agent Fremont] Clear!

48
00:07:15,977 --> 00:07:17,270
Murdock's been home.

49
00:07:18,604 --> 00:07:19,647
Recently.

50
00:07:21,858 --> 00:07:23,901
[woman] It was so nice to see you again.

51
00:07:25,153 --> 00:07:26,237
Take care.

52
00:07:41,627 --> 00:07:42,962
[Karen] Felix Manning?

53
00:07:43,045 --> 00:07:44,881
You haven't returned my calls.

54
00:07:44,964 --> 00:07:46,340
Karen Page, from the <i>Bulletin. </i>

55
00:07:47,300 --> 00:07:48,217
Before I go to print,

56
00:07:48,301 --> 00:07:50,094
I'm obligated to offer you
a chance to comment

57
00:07:50,178 --> 00:07:53,222
on your involvement
in laundering money for Wilson Fisk.

58
00:07:58,311 --> 00:08:02,857
Look, if you talk to me off the record,
help me connect some dots,

59
00:08:02,940 --> 00:08:04,775
I promise I will keep your name out of it.

60
00:08:07,028 --> 00:08:09,655
But that is only if you talk to me.

61
00:08:11,532 --> 00:08:14,368
You're a fixer, Mr. Manning.

62
00:08:15,703 --> 00:08:19,165
You're a freelancer.
Other clients, a lot to lose.

63
00:08:19,248 --> 00:08:22,960
Once this story breaks,
Fisk is gonna hang you out to dry.

64
00:08:24,003 --> 00:08:27,006
If I were you,
I would start looking out for myself.

65
00:08:28,424 --> 00:08:29,759
Karen Page.

66
00:08:29,842 --> 00:08:31,844
Daughter of Paxton and Penelope.

67
00:08:33,054 --> 00:08:37,141
239 Kings Road, Fagan Corners, Vermont.

68
00:08:38,476 --> 00:08:42,980
You had the back room. My guess,
Dad wanted his little girl to be safe.

69
00:08:44,315 --> 00:08:47,193
Sadly, he should've been more worried
about his little boy.

70
00:08:48,653 --> 00:08:51,739
Drug addicts really do destroy families,
don't they?

71
00:08:53,533 --> 00:08:54,784
Off the record,

72
00:08:55,493 --> 00:08:56,953
you're incorrect.

73
00:08:57,995 --> 00:08:59,747
About what I do for a living.

74
00:09:00,790 --> 00:09:02,250
I don't fix problems.

75
00:09:02,750 --> 00:09:04,460
[scribbling]

76
00:09:05,586 --> 00:09:08,172
I make them disappear.

77
00:09:34,657 --> 00:09:35,533
[tires screech]

78
00:09:36,576 --> 00:09:38,452
[Karen breathes heavily]

79
00:09:40,204 --> 00:09:41,581
Karen Page?

80
00:09:42,290 --> 00:09:44,208
-Who are you?
-Don't move.

81
00:09:46,711 --> 00:09:47,712
FBI.

82
00:09:48,504 --> 00:09:52,842
Uh... I have a weapon in my purse.
And a concealed carry permit.

83
00:09:52,925 --> 00:09:56,679
Keep your hands exactly where they are
and follow my instructions.

84
00:09:57,471 --> 00:09:58,931
Now turn around.

85
00:09:59,765 --> 00:10:01,392
[Karen whispering] Okay. Okay.

86
00:10:04,270 --> 00:10:05,605
[breathes heavily]

87
00:10:05,688 --> 00:10:07,690
[Karen] Okay. Okay.

88
00:10:08,190 --> 00:10:10,651
[Karen breathes heavily]

89
00:10:13,446 --> 00:10:14,989
What do you want from me?

90
00:10:23,164 --> 00:10:24,248
What happened?

91
00:10:25,291 --> 00:10:26,876
Why'd you bring me here?

92
00:10:28,502 --> 00:10:29,879
I asked him to.

93
00:10:30,546 --> 00:10:31,547
Is Matt okay?

94
00:10:33,007 --> 00:10:34,634
You wanna tell me what's going on?

95
00:10:35,217 --> 00:10:37,928
Ms. Page, I get that you
ask questions for a living,

96
00:10:38,012 --> 00:10:40,640
but, for now, I'll be the one asking.

97
00:10:56,572 --> 00:10:57,948
[indistinct chatter]

98
00:11:04,538 --> 00:11:06,624
[Ray] When's the last time
you heard from Matt Murdock?

99
00:11:07,208 --> 00:11:08,167
Um...

100
00:11:09,126 --> 00:11:09,960
Months.

101
00:11:10,044 --> 00:11:12,588
You haven't seen
or spoken to him in months?

102
00:11:13,089 --> 00:11:14,298
Uh, no.

103
00:11:16,842 --> 00:11:19,220
He give you any indication
when he'd be back?

104
00:11:21,263 --> 00:11:23,015
[clears throat] Uh, no.

105
00:11:23,557 --> 00:11:25,476
[Ray] Or whether he'd be back at all?

106
00:11:26,143 --> 00:11:28,020
[sighs] No. Then why have you been paying his bills?

107
00:11:37,446 --> 00:11:40,032
He's a friend. Someone had to do it
while he was away.

108
00:11:40,741 --> 00:11:45,621
So your friend, a blind man
who you haven't spoken to in months,

109
00:11:45,705 --> 00:11:49,917
just ups and disappears, and you
don't file a missing persons report?

110
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:52,169
I figured he'd come back
when he was ready.

111
00:11:59,260 --> 00:12:02,263
Can you think of any reason
why Matt Murdock would go on the run?

112
00:12:04,223 --> 00:12:05,224
No.

113
00:12:07,268 --> 00:12:10,271
You were a secretary
for Nelson and Murdock.

114
00:12:10,354 --> 00:12:12,148
Mmm-mmm. Office manager.

115
00:12:13,107 --> 00:12:15,860
And when did the firm
first start working for Wilson Fisk?

116
00:12:15,943 --> 00:12:17,153
Um...

117
00:12:17,236 --> 00:12:19,280
We never worked for Wilson Fisk.

118
00:12:25,870 --> 00:12:27,580
Is that your signature?

119
00:12:27,663 --> 00:12:32,042
Do you remember depositing this
retainer check for a company called CGI?

120
00:12:32,126 --> 00:12:37,131
Yes, I do. Um... Look, Matt and Foggy
took on one case for them. That's all.

121
00:12:37,214 --> 00:12:39,633
According to my source,
CGI was a front for Fisk.

122
00:12:39,717 --> 00:12:41,635
Well, we didn't know that at the time.

123
00:12:42,595 --> 00:12:44,221
But you do now.

124
00:12:45,890 --> 00:12:49,393
So you see how your last answer
wasn't technically accurate?

125
00:12:49,477 --> 00:12:52,146
Okay, we never knowingly worked for Fisk.

126
00:12:52,229 --> 00:12:54,315
They hired us through someone else.

127
00:12:54,398 --> 00:12:55,232
Who?

128
00:12:56,233 --> 00:12:57,276
Some executive.

129
00:12:58,694 --> 00:12:59,695
Hang on.

130
00:13:16,670 --> 00:13:18,339
Was it this guy?

131
00:13:18,422 --> 00:13:20,883
James Wesley. You remember him?

132
00:13:22,802 --> 00:13:25,387
Uh, yeah. I think that was him. Why?

133
00:13:29,517 --> 00:13:31,977
Just trying to put the pieces together.

134
00:13:35,439 --> 00:13:39,026
Okay. Uh... Well, here are some
other pieces for you to put together.

135
00:13:39,777 --> 00:13:40,694
Um...

136
00:13:41,111 --> 00:13:45,574
Felix Manning. Red Lion National Bank.
Vancorp. Any of that ring any bells?

137
00:13:46,492 --> 00:13:47,576
I don't follow.

138
00:13:48,202 --> 00:13:50,704
[Karen] Well, instead of letting Fisk
use you and the FBI

139
00:13:50,788 --> 00:13:53,082
to retaliate against innocent lawyers
who put him in prison,

140
00:13:53,165 --> 00:13:56,168
why don't you ask him if he hired
a fixer named Felix Manning

141
00:13:56,252 --> 00:13:58,379
to launder money through Red Lion?

142
00:13:58,462 --> 00:14:02,383
Ask him if he's the true owner
of a shell company called Vancorp.

143
00:14:03,300 --> 00:14:04,301
Why would I do that?

144
00:14:04,385 --> 00:14:06,720
Because it just bought
the Presidential Hotel.

145
00:14:09,056 --> 00:14:10,724
Where are you getting this from?

146
00:14:11,559 --> 00:14:15,688
I ask questions for a living.
I just ask better ones than you do.

147
00:14:16,647 --> 00:14:21,360
Like, has your so-called prisoner just
bought the prison you're keeping him in?

148
00:14:22,069 --> 00:14:23,320
[chuckles]

149
00:14:23,404 --> 00:14:24,738
Has he bought?

150
00:14:25,364 --> 00:14:29,034
-So this is what? Just a theory?
-[Karen scoffs]

151
00:14:29,118 --> 00:14:30,286
You have any proof?

152
00:14:30,369 --> 00:14:33,289
Fisk is using you, Agent Nadeem.
That's what he does.

153
00:14:33,873 --> 00:14:34,999
Is that a no?

154
00:14:35,958 --> 00:14:37,334
Am I under arrest?

155
00:14:39,295 --> 00:14:40,296
Not at this time.

156
00:14:40,379 --> 00:14:42,756
Then I'm done
answering the wrong questions.

157
00:14:45,593 --> 00:14:47,136
[breathing shakily]

158
00:15:04,486 --> 00:15:05,779
Is this everything?

159
00:15:05,863 --> 00:15:09,491
Everything Felix's investigators
were able to dig up on short notice.

160
00:15:17,166 --> 00:15:18,334
Uh...

161
00:15:26,383 --> 00:15:28,052
This will take some time.

162
00:15:29,094 --> 00:15:30,471
I brought an audiobook.

163
00:15:52,034 --> 00:15:53,327
[Fisk sighs]

164
00:16:03,879 --> 00:16:05,881
[rhythmic tapping]

165
00:16:23,357 --> 00:16:24,692
[man] Dex, ready to go?

166
00:16:24,775 --> 00:16:28,028
Game starts in 20. Traffic's a nightmare.
We gotta hustle.

167
00:16:29,196 --> 00:16:32,616
What's the deal?
You don't even got your uniform on.

168
00:16:35,577 --> 00:16:36,912
You all right, buddy?

169
00:16:40,624 --> 00:16:42,084
Trouble in paradise?

170
00:16:44,128 --> 00:16:47,881
Does the headmaster know you're drilling
a hole in his pile of bricks?

171
00:16:47,965 --> 00:16:49,174
He doesn't like it.

172
00:16:51,885 --> 00:16:54,263
He gives you a hard time,
you send him my way.

173
00:16:54,346 --> 00:16:55,764
It's damn fine practice.

174
00:17:00,728 --> 00:17:02,688
Hey, I got you a little something.

175
00:17:03,939 --> 00:17:05,941
I was gonna wait until after the game...

176
00:17:10,070 --> 00:17:11,655
100% leather.

177
00:17:11,739 --> 00:17:14,742
That's steerhide in the pocket
and cowhide in the palm,

178
00:17:14,825 --> 00:17:16,160
so it's nice and soft.

179
00:17:16,910 --> 00:17:17,953
Try it on.

180
00:17:23,125 --> 00:17:26,503
An all-star pitcher
deserves some all-star gear.

181
00:17:27,713 --> 00:17:29,590
Come on, let's go break it in.

182
00:17:33,010 --> 00:17:34,261
Wait.

183
00:17:34,845 --> 00:17:37,514
Real quick, can I show you my new wind-up?

184
00:17:38,474 --> 00:17:39,349
[chuckles softly]

185
00:17:41,685 --> 00:17:42,936
All right, showboat.

186
00:17:43,479 --> 00:17:44,563
Let's see it.

187
00:17:49,860 --> 00:17:51,612
[indistinct chatter and cheering]

188
00:17:57,659 --> 00:18:00,621
You're in the zone, Dex.
Keep throwing those heaters.

189
00:18:09,129 --> 00:18:10,464
[umpire] Strike!

190
00:18:12,758 --> 00:18:13,801
Strike!

191
00:18:15,177 --> 00:18:16,553
Strike!

192
00:18:17,137 --> 00:18:18,597
Strike! Strike!

193
00:18:20,057 --> 00:18:21,266
Strike!

194
00:18:22,976 --> 00:18:26,897
All right, kiddo. Pack it in.
Let's give that arm of yours a rest.

195
00:18:26,980 --> 00:18:28,482
You're pulling me?

196
00:18:28,565 --> 00:18:33,362
-I'm gonna let Kanon finish it out.
-But... but no one's gotten a hit off me.

197
00:18:33,445 --> 00:18:36,073
I know. You're killin' it out here.
No question.

198
00:18:36,156 --> 00:18:38,575
But I gotta give other kids
some field time.

199
00:18:38,659 --> 00:18:43,247
You can't do this. It's not fair!
You gotta let me keep going.

200
00:18:43,831 --> 00:18:47,251
Keep it together, okay?
Take a few deep breaths.

201
00:18:48,210 --> 00:18:49,336
Big gulps of air.

202
00:18:50,170 --> 00:18:52,047
[stammers] I need...

203
00:18:52,131 --> 00:18:54,174
I need to keep going.

204
00:18:54,258 --> 00:18:58,262
[sobs] If I pitch a perfect game,
then they might...

205
00:19:00,013 --> 00:19:01,557
[sobbing]

206
00:19:03,976 --> 00:19:05,144
[clicks tongue]

207
00:19:05,894 --> 00:19:06,895
Dex...

208
00:19:08,230 --> 00:19:10,941
you could pitch a billion perfect games.

209
00:19:11,900 --> 00:19:13,652
It won't bring your parents back.

210
00:19:19,616 --> 00:19:20,617
Okay.

211
00:19:22,035 --> 00:19:23,120
Hit the pine.

212
00:19:24,872 --> 00:19:26,123
Grab a Popsicle.

213
00:19:26,874 --> 00:19:27,875
We'll talk later.

214
00:20:18,550 --> 00:20:21,178
[Mercer] <i>Well, this has been nice so far,</i>
<i>hasn't it?</i>

215
00:20:21,261 --> 00:20:22,471
<i>Talking like this.</i>

216
00:20:23,639 --> 00:20:25,682
Now that we've gotten to know
each other a little bit,

217
00:20:25,766 --> 00:20:28,518
I wonder if we could talk
about Coach Bradley?

218
00:20:32,022 --> 00:20:34,524
What happened at the field?

219
00:20:36,610 --> 00:20:38,278
How did it make you feel?

220
00:20:39,571 --> 00:20:40,572
Sad?

221
00:20:41,406 --> 00:20:43,200
Maybe a little scared? I wasn't sad.

222
00:20:46,703 --> 00:20:48,622
Why not, do you think?

223
00:20:48,705 --> 00:20:50,123
He was a jerk.

224
00:20:51,875 --> 00:20:52,834
How so?

225
00:20:53,252 --> 00:20:55,087
How was Coach Bradley a jerk?

226
00:20:57,506 --> 00:20:59,383
He never let me do what I wanted.

227
00:21:00,050 --> 00:21:02,344
Didn't know shit about pitching.

228
00:21:02,427 --> 00:21:06,431
He was your coach for a long time.
Was he always such a jerk to you?

229
00:21:06,515 --> 00:21:09,309
What about last year
when he named you MVP?

230
00:21:09,393 --> 00:21:10,936
Was he a jerk then?

231
00:21:11,019 --> 00:21:13,188
No. He used to be awesome.

232
00:21:20,153 --> 00:21:22,823
[Mercer] Dex, tell me...

233
00:21:22,906 --> 00:21:24,449
And be honest.

234
00:21:24,533 --> 00:21:26,827
We like honesty around here.

235
00:21:30,038 --> 00:21:32,916
When you hit Coach Bradley...

236
00:21:35,168 --> 00:21:36,670
was that an accident?

237
00:21:39,214 --> 00:21:42,426
Whatever you say stays between us.
That's the law.

238
00:21:48,265 --> 00:21:49,641
No.

239
00:21:49,725 --> 00:21:51,393
It wasn't an accident.

240
00:21:59,484 --> 00:22:00,819
Am I in trouble?

241
00:22:01,778 --> 00:22:02,779
No.

242
00:22:03,780 --> 00:22:04,614
No.

243
00:22:05,866 --> 00:22:06,992
It wasn't your fault.

244
00:22:07,075 --> 00:22:11,413
But I just told you, I did it on purpose.

245
00:22:11,496 --> 00:22:13,206
That doesn't mean it was your fault.

246
00:22:14,416 --> 00:22:16,585
It's confusing, isn't it?

247
00:22:17,377 --> 00:22:19,463
Here, let me put it like this.

248
00:22:20,339 --> 00:22:22,007
This is you, right?

249
00:22:22,090 --> 00:22:23,050
Yeah.

250
00:22:23,133 --> 00:22:24,760
This is fantastic.

251
00:22:26,345 --> 00:22:28,305
But you see how alone you are?

252
00:22:29,056 --> 00:22:32,351
It's just you,
surrounded by all this emptiness.

253
00:22:34,186 --> 00:22:37,564
It's been that way
for most of your life, hasn't it?

254
00:22:39,149 --> 00:22:40,275
Yeah.

255
00:22:40,359 --> 00:22:43,653
I mean, most kids, they have moms or dads

256
00:22:43,737 --> 00:22:47,532
to teach them right from wrong,
to show them how to behave.

257
00:22:49,534 --> 00:22:52,913
My parents mostly got mad at me.

258
00:22:52,996 --> 00:22:53,955
Yes.

259
00:22:54,039 --> 00:22:55,749
Then they died.

260
00:22:56,291 --> 00:22:58,919
And there were things
that you never learned.

261
00:22:59,711 --> 00:23:00,754
You see?

262
00:23:01,296 --> 00:23:02,506
Not your fault.

263
00:23:03,340 --> 00:23:06,468
Good news is, you've got me now.

264
00:23:07,636 --> 00:23:13,183
Now, we've got a lot of work to do,
but I think that it is going to be fun.

265
00:23:14,434 --> 00:23:17,521
We are going to establish some routines,

266
00:23:18,647 --> 00:23:20,148
learn to stay calm.

267
00:23:21,316 --> 00:23:24,403
And first things first,
we're gonna practice empathy.

268
00:23:24,486 --> 00:23:25,487
What's that?

269
00:23:25,570 --> 00:23:28,824
That means being kind to someone
when they're in pain.

270
00:23:28,907 --> 00:23:33,495
So let's say, for example, that my cat
got sick this morning and I was upset.

271
00:23:34,246 --> 00:23:35,372
What would you say to me?

272
00:23:37,791 --> 00:23:42,337
How about something like,
"I'm sorry. That sounds hard."

273
00:23:43,463 --> 00:23:46,508
I'm sorry. That sounds really hard.

274
00:23:46,591 --> 00:23:48,218
Look at you!

275
00:23:48,301 --> 00:23:50,137
You even put a "really" in there.

276
00:23:50,846 --> 00:23:52,347
I like a fast learner.

277
00:23:55,559 --> 00:23:59,688
I think we are gonna make a terrific team,
you and me.

278
00:24:00,272 --> 00:24:02,399
-[bottle pops open]
-[Mercer] Oh. [laughs]

279
00:24:04,359 --> 00:24:07,612
Nothing marks an occasion
like a little bubbly, huh?

280
00:24:08,780 --> 00:24:12,451
It's a... a Cava, actually.

281
00:24:12,534 --> 00:24:14,077
Spanish champagne.

282
00:24:14,911 --> 00:24:19,249
It was a little farewell gift
from the chiropractor down the hall.

283
00:24:19,958 --> 00:24:22,752
Tomorrow is my last day in the building.

284
00:24:24,588 --> 00:24:25,630
Here. Go on.

285
00:24:26,256 --> 00:24:27,966
I'm not 21.

286
00:24:28,550 --> 00:24:29,801
Good for you.

287
00:24:32,721 --> 00:24:33,722
[Mercer coughing] [sniffs]

288
00:24:39,102 --> 00:24:42,105
It's been quite a challenging day.

289
00:24:43,523 --> 00:24:45,484
Quite a few goodbyes.

290
00:24:46,943 --> 00:24:48,236
Lots of...

291
00:24:49,279 --> 00:24:51,114
longtime clients.

292
00:24:51,198 --> 00:24:52,782
That... That's hard.

293
00:24:53,325 --> 00:24:55,202
That's really hard.

294
00:25:00,373 --> 00:25:01,958
And then there's this,

295
00:25:02,959 --> 00:25:05,212
our last session together,

296
00:25:05,295 --> 00:25:08,298
which I've been dreading
since my prognosis.

297
00:25:08,882 --> 00:25:10,133
Then don't leave.

298
00:25:11,551 --> 00:25:13,595
We can keep meeting.
I can keep getting better.

299
00:25:13,678 --> 00:25:15,096
Dex...

300
00:25:16,014 --> 00:25:17,474
[crying] You can't leave.

301
00:25:17,557 --> 00:25:19,893
[Mercer] You are gonna be fine, Dex.

302
00:25:20,602 --> 00:25:22,354
We prepared for this.

303
00:25:23,271 --> 00:25:26,566
You are gonna get a job
with a nice, rigid structure.

304
00:25:26,650 --> 00:25:28,735
You're gonna stick to your meds.

305
00:25:29,945 --> 00:25:34,533
And if you get off track, you can...
listen to these.

306
00:25:36,993 --> 00:25:39,955
This is every session we've had.

307
00:25:40,539 --> 00:25:42,541
Cycle through them again.

308
00:25:43,333 --> 00:25:46,753
When we remind ourselves
of how far we've come,

309
00:25:46,836 --> 00:25:48,880
we're less inclined to slip back.

310
00:25:50,257 --> 00:25:51,841
And one last thing.

311
00:25:53,176 --> 00:25:56,888
This is a, uh... a colleague of mine.

312
00:25:56,972 --> 00:26:02,060
He's a fine therapist, with a lot
of expertise in your particular--

313
00:26:02,143 --> 00:26:04,396
I don't want another therapist!

314
00:26:06,773 --> 00:26:08,483
Are you trying to scare me?

315
00:26:09,025 --> 00:26:10,110
No.

316
00:26:11,236 --> 00:26:12,529
Not scare you.

317
00:26:12,612 --> 00:26:14,531
Then what is your intention?

318
00:26:16,074 --> 00:26:17,409
And be honest.

319
00:26:18,243 --> 00:26:19,619
I want...

320
00:26:24,541 --> 00:26:26,459
I want to kill you.

321
00:26:26,543 --> 00:26:27,669
[Mercer] Say more.

322
00:26:28,587 --> 00:26:30,380
Why do you want to kill me?

323
00:26:31,047 --> 00:26:32,841
To put me out of my misery?

324
00:26:35,218 --> 00:26:36,928
To punish you.

325
00:26:37,012 --> 00:26:39,389
I'm not quite sure what I've done wrong.

326
00:26:39,472 --> 00:26:42,809
I want to kill you for dying.

327
00:26:44,686 --> 00:26:46,229
For leaving me.

328
00:26:48,857 --> 00:26:51,693
Death always wins, Dex.

329
00:26:53,278 --> 00:26:54,613
Eventually.

330
00:26:56,531 --> 00:27:01,536
But when it comes quietly and naturally,
it can be a beautiful event.

331
00:27:02,621 --> 00:27:06,499
Which is why
we never hasten it with violence.

332
00:27:09,961 --> 00:27:10,962
[breathes shakily]

333
00:27:12,672 --> 00:27:14,466
I can't do this alone.

334
00:27:15,800 --> 00:27:17,177
[coughs, inhales]

335
00:27:18,428 --> 00:27:20,388
You remember what I did?

336
00:27:21,931 --> 00:27:23,850
Last time I was alone?

337
00:27:23,933 --> 00:27:25,393
Then find someone.

338
00:27:25,477 --> 00:27:27,187
I don't want another therapist!

339
00:27:27,270 --> 00:27:30,106
Any good person
with a decent heart will do.

340
00:27:30,690 --> 00:27:32,442
Someone to look up to.

341
00:27:35,779 --> 00:27:38,281
Your internal compass isn't broken, Dex.

342
00:27:38,365 --> 00:27:43,578
It just works better when you have
the North Star to guide you.

343
00:27:49,876 --> 00:27:50,877
[telephone ringing]

344
00:28:01,805 --> 00:28:03,723
Suicide Prevention, this is Dex.

345
00:28:03,807 --> 00:28:05,141
Who am I speaking with?

346
00:28:06,518 --> 00:28:09,020
Hi, Craig. How can I help you today?

347
00:28:12,357 --> 00:28:14,943
I'm sorry. That's hard.
That's really hard.

348
00:28:15,568 --> 00:28:18,780
Why don't you tell me a little bit more
about how you're feeling?

349
00:28:18,863 --> 00:28:22,117
That's a lot to deal with.
I'm glad you called.

350
00:28:23,243 --> 00:28:24,828
[whispering] You're doing amazing.

351
00:28:29,374 --> 00:28:30,500
[Dex] Tell me, Craig,

352
00:28:31,167 --> 00:28:33,837
are you thinking
about taking your own life right now?

353
00:28:34,462 --> 00:28:35,505
Okay.

354
00:28:39,175 --> 00:28:40,510
Do you have a plan?

355
00:28:50,478 --> 00:28:52,522
What kind of gun do you have, Craig?

356
00:28:56,109 --> 00:28:57,944
I'm familiar with the M11.

357
00:28:58,611 --> 00:29:02,031
Did a couple years in the army.
Got real cozy with the M11.

358
00:29:02,907 --> 00:29:04,242
It's reliable.

359
00:29:08,621 --> 00:29:10,790
Let me ask you a question, Craig.

360
00:29:11,708 --> 00:29:15,336
If this asshole stepdad of yours
is giving you so much grief,

361
00:29:16,129 --> 00:29:17,756
why take your own life?

362
00:29:18,423 --> 00:29:19,507
Why not...

363
00:29:20,300 --> 00:29:21,134
[inhales sharply]

364
00:29:21,217 --> 00:29:23,470
Take a deep breath, Craig.

365
00:29:24,554 --> 00:29:26,681
We're gonna work through this together.

366
00:29:27,974 --> 00:29:29,559
I'm not going anywhere.

367
00:30:36,376 --> 00:30:38,419
If I may ask, Mr. Fisk,

368
00:30:38,503 --> 00:30:42,549
without getting into specifics,
what's this all about?

369
00:30:48,596 --> 00:30:51,391
Right now, I am New York's scapegoat.

370
00:30:53,226 --> 00:30:56,062
Downstairs, there are protesters
chanting prayers

371
00:30:56,145 --> 00:30:58,940
to drive me out into the wilderness.

372
00:31:00,024 --> 00:31:04,195
The attention that it brings
is an impediment for my plan.

373
00:31:05,405 --> 00:31:08,950
Fortunately,
the public is easily distracted. Which makes the solution
for my problem quite simple.

374
00:31:17,584 --> 00:31:19,669
The city needs a new villain.

375
00:31:25,049 --> 00:31:27,427
And I think I might've found him.

376
00:31:31,848 --> 00:31:33,850
[Julie] Can I start you off
with something to drink?

377
00:31:39,063 --> 00:31:41,149
Looks like you need a little more time.

378
00:31:42,650 --> 00:31:44,569
I'll grab you a water.

379
00:31:46,112 --> 00:31:47,780
This is gonna sound random,

380
00:31:47,864 --> 00:31:50,742
but did you used to work
at the Brooklyn Suicide Hotline?

381
00:31:52,619 --> 00:31:57,165
Yeah. Yeah, I did.
That... was a tough job. [chuckles]

382
00:31:58,166 --> 00:31:59,459
It was. [chuckles]

383
00:32:00,627 --> 00:32:04,130
You probably don't remember me. I'm Julie.

384
00:32:07,884 --> 00:32:08,885
Dex.

385
00:32:09,969 --> 00:32:11,930
Yeah, of course I remember you.

386
00:32:12,889 --> 00:32:14,307
Small world, huh?

387
00:32:15,266 --> 00:32:17,977
I haven't seen you in here before.

388
00:32:18,061 --> 00:32:21,481
It's... it's my first day, actually.

389
00:32:21,564 --> 00:32:23,608
I got offered double the pay
to leave my last job

390
00:32:23,691 --> 00:32:27,195
if I could start here immediately.
Not that I'm complaining.

391
00:32:28,863 --> 00:32:31,199
What about you?
Are you staying at the hotel?

392
00:32:31,866 --> 00:32:34,285
[stammers] No. I live here.

393
00:32:34,369 --> 00:32:36,704
In New York, not in the hotel.

394
00:32:36,788 --> 00:32:37,830
[both laughing]

395
00:32:37,914 --> 00:32:39,916
The FBI has an office upstairs.

396
00:32:41,417 --> 00:32:43,294
We're guarding Wilson Fisk.

397
00:32:44,420 --> 00:32:45,713
A G-man.

398
00:32:45,797 --> 00:32:48,675
-[Dex chuckles softly]
-[woman] Excuse me, miss! Hello?

399
00:32:51,844 --> 00:32:55,974
I need to go help that table
so they don't fire me on my first day.

400
00:32:56,849 --> 00:32:58,518
What time do you get off?

401
00:33:00,186 --> 00:33:01,604
In about an hour.

402
00:33:03,022 --> 00:33:04,857
Do you wanna hang out after?

403
00:33:04,941 --> 00:33:06,109
Catch up?

404
00:33:07,777 --> 00:33:08,611
Uh...

405
00:33:09,404 --> 00:33:10,655
Yeah. [chuckles]

406
00:33:11,572 --> 00:33:13,116
That... That'd be great.

407
00:33:14,617 --> 00:33:15,451
Hmm.

408
00:33:23,126 --> 00:33:28,214
I got your coppa, your prosciutto,
your mocetta, your sweet soppressata.

409
00:33:28,297 --> 00:33:30,174
All you can eat. Free!

410
00:33:30,258 --> 00:33:33,052
For anybody who promises
to vote for Foggy Nelson,

411
00:33:33,136 --> 00:33:35,179
my less handsome brother.

412
00:33:36,180 --> 00:33:37,807
You can't do that, Theo.

413
00:33:37,890 --> 00:33:41,352
It violates election law.
It's an illegal inducement to vote.

414
00:33:41,436 --> 00:33:44,272
I don't see Mrs. Wobschall
calling the cops.

415
00:33:44,355 --> 00:33:45,189
[laughs]

416
00:33:45,273 --> 00:33:46,733
May I borrow a pen?

417
00:33:55,324 --> 00:33:57,201
Is that an actual ballot, Mrs. Callahan?

418
00:33:57,952 --> 00:33:59,370
I just voted for you.

419
00:33:59,454 --> 00:34:00,455
Absentee.

420
00:34:01,122 --> 00:34:05,251
When Wilson Fisk set off
those explosives in Hell's Kitchen,

421
00:34:05,334 --> 00:34:06,502
I lost my husband.

422
00:34:06,586 --> 00:34:08,880
Everything that matters, gone.

423
00:34:08,963 --> 00:34:10,465
Except my vote.

424
00:34:11,632 --> 00:34:15,136
I'm counting on you, Foggy.
You get that son of a bitch.

425
00:34:16,137 --> 00:34:18,473
I will. I promise.

426
00:34:22,685 --> 00:34:24,103
Thank you, everyone.

427
00:34:24,187 --> 00:34:26,981
And I'll be here till close
to answer any questions.

428
00:34:27,607 --> 00:34:29,358
Yeah, I got a few.

429
00:34:29,442 --> 00:34:33,112
Like, what's the secret ingredient
in your world-famous Nelson's sub?

430
00:34:33,863 --> 00:34:36,240
A soft robiola.

431
00:34:36,324 --> 00:34:37,784
[inhales and exhales]

432
00:34:37,867 --> 00:34:40,828
Perfect. Uh, team at work
is gonna love that.

433
00:34:40,912 --> 00:34:41,829
Uh...

434
00:34:41,913 --> 00:34:42,914
Give me six.

435
00:34:43,498 --> 00:34:47,001
Uh, Theo can help you at the counter.
Is there anything else?

436
00:34:47,085 --> 00:34:48,086
Yeah.

437
00:34:49,087 --> 00:34:50,922
When's the last time you saw Matt Murdock?

438
00:34:53,091 --> 00:34:54,092
Who are you?

439
00:34:59,806 --> 00:35:02,975
[Foggy] Crashing my campaign event,
trying to intimidate me,

440
00:35:03,059 --> 00:35:05,311
dropping the names of my friends...

441
00:35:05,978 --> 00:35:10,191
I'm not backing off my criticism
of the feds' love affair with Fisk!

442
00:35:12,860 --> 00:35:15,196
You seem like a decent guy, Mr. Nelson.

443
00:35:16,155 --> 00:35:19,283
You care about people.
About doing the right thing.

444
00:35:20,868 --> 00:35:22,745
I'm guessing that's why
you ditched Matt Murdock

445
00:35:22,829 --> 00:35:25,164
as your law partner in the first place.

446
00:35:25,248 --> 00:35:26,457
Am I correct?

447
00:35:27,667 --> 00:35:30,670
You really think I'm gonna answer
a question that leading?

448
00:35:31,295 --> 00:35:34,048
To be clear:
did you dissolve your partnership

449
00:35:34,132 --> 00:35:36,759
because Mr. Murdock
took on Wilson Fisk as a client?

450
00:35:36,843 --> 00:35:39,011
If you're referring to a single case

451
00:35:39,095 --> 00:35:42,598
where we represented a client
who allegedly worked for Fisk

452
00:35:42,682 --> 00:35:45,434
even though we didn't know
that at the time...

453
00:35:45,518 --> 00:35:46,602
the answer's no.

454
00:35:47,728 --> 00:35:49,438
It had nothing to do with it.

455
00:35:49,522 --> 00:35:52,275
Nelson and Murdock
represented a lot of clients,

456
00:35:52,358 --> 00:35:55,862
for whom all work
was completely ethical and legal

457
00:35:55,945 --> 00:35:58,281
and protected
by attorney-client privilege.

458
00:35:59,824 --> 00:36:01,909
When's the last time you saw Matt Murdock?

459
00:36:05,621 --> 00:36:06,956
Two nights ago.

460
00:36:07,790 --> 00:36:08,791
Where?

461
00:36:08,875 --> 00:36:10,877
A bar in Hell's Kitchen.

462
00:36:10,960 --> 00:36:12,545
And what did you discuss?

463
00:36:14,589 --> 00:36:16,632
That we hadn't seen each other in a while.

464
00:36:16,716 --> 00:36:19,093
-Did he tell you where he was going?
-No.

465
00:36:19,177 --> 00:36:20,720
-Where you could find him?
-No.

466
00:36:21,512 --> 00:36:22,680
Did he tell you anything?

467
00:36:23,598 --> 00:36:25,016
That he was sorry.

468
00:36:26,142 --> 00:36:27,226
About what?

469
00:36:27,852 --> 00:36:30,229
That our friendship
isn't what it used to be.

470
00:36:32,064 --> 00:36:34,984
So you didn't knowingly
give him your bar ID?

471
00:36:35,610 --> 00:36:36,611
What?

472
00:36:38,654 --> 00:36:39,488
[sighs]

473
00:36:40,531 --> 00:36:41,824
Of course not. Why would I?

474
00:36:44,702 --> 00:36:47,997
So he could enter a prison,
falsely using your identity,

475
00:36:48,080 --> 00:36:50,041
and make contact with an Albanian gang

476
00:36:50,124 --> 00:36:52,627
linked to the murder
of nine federal agents.

477
00:36:54,921 --> 00:36:56,214
I...

478
00:36:56,839 --> 00:36:59,675
I didn't give him my ID.

479
00:37:00,635 --> 00:37:03,638
Nor was I aware of anything
that he was planning.

480
00:37:05,473 --> 00:37:07,099
But with all due respect,

481
00:37:07,683 --> 00:37:10,603
-I think you have Matt Murdock all wrong.
-[scoffs]

482
00:37:10,686 --> 00:37:12,063
Yeah, well, uh...

483
00:37:13,356 --> 00:37:14,732
I don't think I do.

484
00:37:15,942 --> 00:37:18,694
I think Matt Murdock
is hiding a double life.

485
00:37:19,278 --> 00:37:22,198
Lawyer by day and criminal by night.

486
00:37:23,407 --> 00:37:26,244
And you and Ms. Page
both know all about it.

487
00:37:27,620 --> 00:37:29,455
It makes you uncomfortable.

488
00:37:29,538 --> 00:37:30,706
And complicit.

489
00:37:31,332 --> 00:37:34,585
And that's why you're no longer
law partners or friends.

490
00:37:34,669 --> 00:37:36,629
Because once he's finally caught,

491
00:37:36,712 --> 00:37:40,174
you know you're on the hook
as an accessory to his crimes.

492
00:37:40,258 --> 00:37:43,844
Or, if you're lucky,
simply aiding and abetting.

493
00:37:45,554 --> 00:37:48,891
Remind me, Special Agent Nadeem,

494
00:37:50,017 --> 00:37:51,727
what's Matt being charged with?

495
00:37:52,645 --> 00:37:53,980
Nothing so far.

496
00:37:54,063 --> 00:37:55,106
Great.

497
00:37:56,023 --> 00:37:59,986
Then the only thing
I'm aiding and abetting is your exit.

498
00:38:16,210 --> 00:38:17,712
Don't forget to vote.

499
00:38:20,256 --> 00:38:21,674
[Julie] <i>Every day?</i>

500
00:38:21,757 --> 00:38:22,800
[chuckles]

501
00:38:22,883 --> 00:38:24,719
FDR Drive's my favorite route, too.

502
00:38:24,802 --> 00:38:27,305
There's nothing in the world
like a winter run on the East River.

503
00:38:27,888 --> 00:38:31,517
Between your workout habits
and new gig, it's...

504
00:38:31,600 --> 00:38:33,644
it's almost like you're stalking me.

505
00:38:33,728 --> 00:38:34,812
[laughs]

506
00:38:34,895 --> 00:38:36,856
Damn. The secret's out.

507
00:38:39,400 --> 00:38:40,443
So...

508
00:38:41,068 --> 00:38:43,195
why aren't you in social work anymore?

509
00:38:43,904 --> 00:38:44,739
Uh...

510
00:38:44,822 --> 00:38:46,907
Tried to pursue my dream as a dancer.

511
00:38:47,700 --> 00:38:51,662
It actually was going pretty well
until I tore my ACL, again.

512
00:38:52,246 --> 00:38:55,499
I'm sorry. That must've been really hard.

513
00:38:55,583 --> 00:38:58,085
But you were brave to go for it
in the first place.

514
00:38:59,045 --> 00:39:00,046
I, um...

515
00:39:00,713 --> 00:39:02,506
I didn't have a backup plan.

516
00:39:03,090 --> 00:39:06,260
My parents made the mistake of telling me
I could be anything I wanted.

517
00:39:06,344 --> 00:39:09,055
Must've been nice to hear,
even if it didn't work out.

518
00:39:11,432 --> 00:39:15,227
My parents
were never really that involved.

519
00:39:17,063 --> 00:39:19,523
Sounds like you didn't need
the message anyhow.

520
00:39:20,816 --> 00:39:22,651
You did great all on your own.

521
00:39:26,238 --> 00:39:27,073
[chuckles]

522
00:39:28,157 --> 00:39:32,370
So, what's it like
working for Wilson Fisk?

523
00:39:33,162 --> 00:39:37,583
I don't work for him.
I work for the federal government.

524
00:39:39,794 --> 00:39:44,048
Must be scary to be up close and personal
with someone so dangerous.

525
00:39:44,131 --> 00:39:45,508
It is what it is.

526
00:39:47,635 --> 00:39:50,262
Do you think a killer like that
deserves a second chance?

527
00:39:51,555 --> 00:39:53,974
You worked at the hotline for three years.

528
00:39:54,058 --> 00:39:57,436
I think you of all people would believe
everyone deserves a second chance.

529
00:39:57,520 --> 00:39:59,480
How did you know
I worked there for three years?

530
00:40:00,064 --> 00:40:01,524
You were only there for one.

531
00:40:02,942 --> 00:40:04,652
You mentioned it earlier.

532
00:40:05,945 --> 00:40:07,905
You quit to do ballet.

533
00:40:07,988 --> 00:40:10,282
Did I also mention ballet earlier?

534
00:40:11,075 --> 00:40:12,410
Specifically?

535
00:40:13,285 --> 00:40:15,913
I guess I... I just assumed.

536
00:40:17,373 --> 00:40:18,374
[chuckles softly] Anyway, um...

537
00:40:21,252 --> 00:40:23,879
It's late. I should get home.

538
00:40:23,963 --> 00:40:25,381
You're ditching me?

539
00:40:25,464 --> 00:40:27,341
No, not at all. I...

540
00:40:28,092 --> 00:40:29,718
I just have to go feed my dog.

541
00:40:29,802 --> 00:40:31,345
You don't have a dog.

542
00:40:32,847 --> 00:40:34,223
How do you know that?

543
00:40:37,309 --> 00:40:39,103
Julie, you're misreading this.

544
00:40:39,186 --> 00:40:40,187
Let me pay for dinner.

545
00:40:40,271 --> 00:40:42,481
We'll go for a walk in the park.
I'll explain.

546
00:40:42,565 --> 00:40:43,691
Dinner's on me.

547
00:40:43,774 --> 00:40:44,775
Julie.

548
00:40:45,443 --> 00:40:47,236
You're very special to me.

549
00:40:47,319 --> 00:40:48,696
Let go of me, Dex.

550
00:40:48,779 --> 00:40:49,613
Please.

551
00:40:49,697 --> 00:40:51,449
I said let go!

552
00:40:52,116 --> 00:40:53,367
[Dex breathing heavily]

553
00:41:02,501 --> 00:41:05,504
Just being at Matt's apartment,
and his bloody clothes...

554
00:41:05,588 --> 00:41:06,839
And I just-- It threw me.

555
00:41:07,423 --> 00:41:10,926
Nadeem's smart. I probably gave him
everything he needs to figure it out.

556
00:41:11,010 --> 00:41:13,596
Wait. You told the FBI
that Matt is Daredevil?

557
00:41:13,679 --> 00:41:15,055
No, no. Of course not.

558
00:41:16,307 --> 00:41:18,601
[sighs] They know he's hiding something.

559
00:41:18,684 --> 00:41:20,311
It's not what they think, but this is bad.

560
00:41:20,394 --> 00:41:22,062
This is really bad. Infinitely bad.

561
00:41:22,146 --> 00:41:23,522
-We could all go to jail.
-Foggy--

562
00:41:23,606 --> 00:41:25,566
I should've never let Matt
tell you his secret.

563
00:41:25,649 --> 00:41:27,401
This is my fault.

564
00:41:27,485 --> 00:41:30,404
I'm not gonna let you pay
for our shitty mistakes.

565
00:41:30,488 --> 00:41:32,907
If it comes to it,
I'll plead in exchange for your immunity.

566
00:41:32,990 --> 00:41:34,116
Foggy...

567
00:41:36,702 --> 00:41:38,204
You always see the good in people.

568
00:41:38,287 --> 00:41:42,041
But you put us on such high pedestals,
you can't see who we really are.

569
00:41:42,625 --> 00:41:45,920
I didn't tell the FBI Matt is Daredevil.
I did something worse.

570
00:41:46,003 --> 00:41:47,671
Karen, breathe.

571
00:41:48,672 --> 00:41:50,132
I'm in trouble.

572
00:41:50,216 --> 00:41:51,759
Tell me what happened.

573
00:41:53,552 --> 00:41:56,305
I'm gonna need attorney-client privilege
before I can.

574
00:41:57,765 --> 00:42:00,726
Okay, um, give me five bucks.

575
00:42:08,067 --> 00:42:09,360
[breathing heavily]

576
00:42:09,443 --> 00:42:12,029
Good enough. I'm officially your lawyer.

577
00:42:16,909 --> 00:42:19,328
Do you remember the... the Healy trial?

578
00:42:20,579 --> 00:42:24,458
And there was that...
that guy from... from CGI

579
00:42:24,542 --> 00:42:28,295
who offered us a stupid amount of money
to take his case?

580
00:42:28,921 --> 00:42:30,798
Yeah, how could I forget that creep?

581
00:42:31,590 --> 00:42:33,300
His name's James Wesley.

582
00:42:34,385 --> 00:42:35,719
He worked for Fisk.

583
00:42:37,388 --> 00:42:38,806
He disappeared shortly after that,

584
00:42:38,889 --> 00:42:40,766
and they think
Matt had something to do with it.

585
00:42:41,600 --> 00:42:44,436
That's crazy.
Matt had nothing to do with that.

586
00:42:44,520 --> 00:42:48,148
I know. But if they keep investigating,
they're gonna find out that I did.

587
00:42:48,691 --> 00:42:49,525
What?

588
00:42:54,071 --> 00:42:55,239
I killed him.

589
00:43:37,781 --> 00:43:38,616
[yells]

590
00:43:39,742 --> 00:43:40,743
[breathing heavily]

591
00:43:53,255 --> 00:43:55,382
Shit. Shit.

592
00:44:01,388 --> 00:44:02,222
[groans] [yelling]

593
00:44:30,042 --> 00:44:31,710
-[yells]
-[cutlery clattering]

594
00:44:43,472 --> 00:44:44,306
[yells]

595
00:44:54,191 --> 00:44:56,193
[breathing heavily]

596
00:45:06,662 --> 00:45:09,373
[Mercer] <i>It's good to see you, Dex.</i>
<i>How was your week?</i>

597
00:45:09,915 --> 00:45:11,667
[young Dex] <i>I'm scared, Dr. Mercer.</i>

598
00:45:12,292 --> 00:45:15,087
[Mercer] <i>Scared? What's making you scared?</i>

599
00:46:16,064 --> 00:46:16,899
[groans]

600
00:46:31,121 --> 00:46:32,706
[Ray] Alpha Team on approach.

601
00:46:37,336 --> 00:46:40,047
[Ray] FBI. Get back in your apartment
and close the door.

602
00:46:40,130 --> 00:46:41,131
[door closes] [Ray] Stack up.

603
00:46:47,596 --> 00:46:48,889
Breach.

604
00:46:50,432 --> 00:46:51,433
[FBI agent] FBI!

605
00:46:51,975 --> 00:46:52,810
Clear!

606
00:46:55,938 --> 00:46:57,231
Murdock's been home.

607
00:46:58,315 --> 00:46:59,358
Recently.

608
00:47:00,192 --> 00:47:03,237
Command post, we're clear.
Suspect's not here.

609
00:47:05,197 --> 00:47:08,158
[woman over police radio]
<i>NYPD has been advised. Citywide BOLO.</i>

610
00:47:08,242 --> 00:47:11,537
<i>Suspect Matthew Murdock</i>
<i>to be considered armed and dangerous.</i>

